President Reagan said he would veto aHouse-passed trade bill requiring mandatory retaliation for"unfair trade" if it reached its desk in its present form.    In a statement at a White House meeting with SenateRepublicans on the legislation, he said: "I would have no choicebut to veto that bill in its present form."    He said the measure "would move us exactly in the wrongdirection" towards high tariffs, trade barriers, tradedistorting subsidies, slow growth and crimped world markets,and would destroy jobs. Reuter&#3;